value.0: Pale and wispy, this ghostly dwarf bears a horrible gash down his left side. His entrails dangle from the broken bridge into the vast darkness below. The uniform he wears is all too familiar to you.
"<FirstName>!" he barks, his voice gruff and dry. "Thank the gods ye've come. Ye be in grave danger, <lad/lass>."
"Blast ye, <FirstName>!" You turn from him and begin to walk away. "Fine, go then, but beware the Night Hag," he calls after you. "Whatever you do, do not trust her!"
He eyes you warily, then spits into the void. "Beware the Night Hag, ye hear? She's not to be trusted."

The dwarf seizes you within his meaty hands. "Don't be a fool! Prince Ahmed never died." Within their ghostly sockets, the dwarf's eyes are manic. You can feel his dangling entrails press against you.
"Because Prince Ahmed never died." Within their ghostly sockets, the dwarf's eyes are manic. His nervous fingers clutch at his dangling entrails.

"I be searching for him here, among the dead. He not be among us, I swear. Not that I can find... I don't know what it means, <FirstName>, but it can't be good. Not with a creature like the Hag about."

"Aye, I be searching for him here, among the dead. He not be among us, I swear. Not that I can find... I don't know what it means, <FirstName>, but it can't be good. Not with a creature like the Hag about."

The dwarf shifts his weight, sending a pebble cascading off into the dark below. "Leave me be," he urges. "I'll continue looking for the Prince. As for ye... Just mind my words around the Night Hag, all right?"
"Harrumph." He crosses his arms over his savage wound and turns to stare off into the void.
He nods in agreement, crosses his arms over his savage wound, and turns to stare off into the void.
He reels back, shocked. "Liar! Lies! Get away from me, ye hound! Away!" He seems in a panic, as if suddenly terrified by your presence.

<StartAction>[Failure]</Start> The ghostly dwarf becomes increasingly agitated. He begins to froth at the mouth and, every time you approach, he snaps out to bite you before some unseen force pulls him back.
<StartAction>[Success]</Start> The ghostly dwarf calms visibly. "It just be that I've been searching for him here, among the dead. He not be among us, I swear. Not that I can find..."
"I don't know what it means, <FirstName>, but it can't be good. Not with a creature like the Hag about... I'll continue looking for the Prince. As for ye, just mind my words around the Night Hag."
The dwarf paws his gaping wound. "It be nothing. Well it be enough to kill me but it be nothing now. The pain be almost gone already."
"Uh?" He looks up at you in surprise. "Why, little Eyrie did. She snuck up behind and gutted me while I be battling Turnak. You were there. Look, there be no time for this, <FirstName>."
The dwarf takes a step backward. "By Brogan's axe! It be me, Morrius Helmsplitter! If ye not remember, then ye be in graver danger yet."
Morrius glances over his shoulder. "I guess I be meeting him soon enough. He be a dwarven hero of the Northern Clans. When he died, he made a bargain with the Stygian Lords."
"He fought for them as a gladiator and, in return, they let him live for as long as he could still fight. In the end, they say he fought four dragons of the abyss."
"They tore him limb from limb and scattered his parts to the world's far corners... Aye but none of that be mattering right now, <FirstName>. As I keep trying to tell ye, ye be in danger."
"Liar!" he shouts, his foamy spittle filling the air. "LIAR!!! The Prince is not dead, I tell you! Not dead!" He bares his teeth at you as he fumbles with his own viscera, clearly mad.
"Leave me be," he grumbles, "and remember what I told ye."
He reaches for you, his eyes manic. "Witchbane!" he cries. "Ye brought it with ye, didn't ye? The axe! Ye did! Aye, I can feel it in me very bones! Give it to me, I need it!"
"Forget the axe, then!" he fumes. "Go, but ye beware the Night Hag," he calls after you as you turn to leave. "She's not to be trusted!"
"Forget the axe, then!" he fumes, his eyes growing manic once more. "I should have known better than to trust ye. I told ye the Prince not be dead but ye didn't believe me!"
He tugs possessivly at his entrails as if thinking you might steal them from him. He turns from you and stares off into the yawning mists below.
"Forget the axe, then!" he fumes. "Go, but remember what I told ye of the Night Hag," he calls after you as you turn to leave.
"Aye?" he asks, clutching at his torn stomach, his voice suddenly laden with mistrust. "I can feel it, though. It be close... <FirstName>, ye be in grave danger..."
"Aye?" he asks, clutching at his torn stomach, his voice suddenly laden with mistrust. "I can feel it, though. It be close," he grumbles, shuffling off. "Remember what I told ye of the Night Hag..."
The dwarf's hands rise from his torn stomach, grasping for the offered axe. They leave bloody smears across the gilded blade. "Aye, that's it..." he concedes. "But it not be right!"

The dwarf's hands rise from his torn stomach, going for the axe. He heeds your warning, though, his hands floating inches away from the bloody blade. "Aye, that's it..." he concedes. "But it not be right!"
His ghostly hands seize you by the shoulders, sending a chill up your spine. "What have ye done with its magic? There be nothing there! It be but lifeless steel, <FirstName>!"
He gazes into your face, his hands falling resolutely to his sides. "Nay, you're right. Just look at us: We both be but shadows of our former selves. Me dear Witchbane be no different."
"I don't know. Something drained it of its magic. It be nothing but a well-honed blade now." He gazes out over the yawning pit below, trying to mask his tears. "Ye be in grave danger, <FirstName>."
The dwarf looks away but, as he does so, you can see his eyes growing manic once more. "May ye burn in the pits of Stygia, <FirstName>! Ye robbed me Witchbane of its magic! It was mine!"

"I should have known better than to trust ye, ye liar! I told ye the Prince not be dead but ye wouldn't listen!" He tugs possessivly at his entrails as if thinking you might steal them from him and turns away.

His ghostly hands seize you by the shoulders, sending a chill up your spine. "What have ye done with its magic? There be nothing there! It be but lifeless steel, <FirstName>!"
"Goodbye."
"Me in danger? How that be?"
"What kind of danger am I in?"
"Yuh? Why me trust you?"
"And trust you instead?"
"That be stupid."
"That's nonsense."
"Huh? How come?"
"Why not?"
"What difference that make?"
"What does that have to do with anything?"
"Yuh, you think so?"
"Oh really?"
"Me mind what me wish."
"I'll mind what I want."
"Thanks. Me keep eye out."
"Thanks, I'll keep an eye out."
"Yuh he did. Me saw him die."
"Yes he did. I saw him die."
Leave him be.
